cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Object-Oriented Approach\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 14:* Let’s use arrays to implement matrices and their associated mathematical operations. Create a class `Matrix` that implements basic matrix arithmetic.\n\nIn Python, a class is defined using the `class` keyword. \n- The `__init__` method initializes the object.\n- Methods like `add(self, other)` take `self` (the current object) and `other` (another matrix).\n- You should validate dimensions before attempting operations (e.g., adding a 2x3 matrix to a 3x3 matrix should raise an error).\n\n### Recursive Cofactor Expansion\nTo find the determinant of a 3x3 matrix, we expand along the top row, multiplying each element by the determinant of the 2x2 submatrix (cofactor) that remains when you cross out its row and column. The signs alternate: $+ - + - \\dots$"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. If $A$ is $2 \\times 3$ and $B$ is $3 \\times 4$, what are the dimensions of $A \\times B$?\n2. What is the base case for the recursive determinant algorithm?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. $2 \\times 4$. The number of columns in A must match the number of rows in B.\n2. A $1 \\times 1$ matrix. Its determinant is just its single element. (Alternatively, a $2 \\times 2$ matrix, where the determinant is $ad-bc$).\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: 2x2 Determinant\nGiven matrix $A = \\begin{bmatrix} 4 & 5 \\\\ 7 & 8 \\end{bmatrix}$. Compute its determinant by hand.\n\nThen write a simple function that computes the determinant of any 2x2 array `[[a,b],[c,d]]`."),
