cell("markdown","### Chalkboard Defense\nExplain the time complexity of your recursive determinant algorithm for an $N \\times N$ matrix. Why is this unacceptably slow for $N=10$?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Sketch</summary>\nComputing an $N \\times N$ determinant requires computing $N$ determinants of size $(N-1) \\times (N-1)$.\nThis yields a recurrence relation roughly equivalent to $O(N!)$ time complexity.\nFor $N=10$, $10! = 3.6$ million operations, which is slow but manageable. For $N=20$, $20! \approx 2.4 \\times 10^{18}$, which would take hundreds of years. We need a faster way (RREF!)\n</details>\n\n---\n📚 **Next:** Algorithms 15 (Reduced Row Echelon Form)")
