cell("markdown","# Algorithms 16: K-Means Clustering\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Understand unsupervised learning and clustering\n2. Implement the iterative K-Means algorithm\n3. Use Euclidean distance to assign data points to clusters\n4. Use the Elbow Method to determine the optimal number of clusters $K$\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 11\n**Estimated time:** 90 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 16"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The K-Means Algorithm\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 16:* K-means clustering groups similar records together. It guesses initial clusters, and repeatedly updates them to make them more cohesive.\n\n1. **Initialize:** Randomly divide the data into $K$ parts (clusters). Compute the center (mean) of each part.\n2. **Assign:** Loop through all data points. Re-assign each point to the cluster whose center is closest (using Euclidean distance).\n3. **Update:** Compute the new center for each cluster by taking the mean of all points newly assigned to it.\n4. **Repeat:** Repeat Assign & Update until the cluster assignments stop changing.\n\n### The Elbow Method\nHow do we choose $K$? If $K = N$ (number of points), every point is its own cluster (distance=0, but useless). \nWe plot the **Total Distance** (sum of distances from each point to its cluster center) against $K$. The curve goes down. We pick the \"elbow\" of the curve — the point of diminishing returns."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. If a cluster loses all its points during the \"Assign\" phase, what happens to its center?\n2. Why does the Total Distance always decrease as $K$ increases?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. The mean of 0 points is undefined (division by zero)! You must handle this edge case (e.g. by re-assigning the center randomly, or keeping its old position).\n2. More clusters mean more centers spread throughout the data. Each point has a higher chance of having a center very close to it.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Euclidean Distance & Centroids\nGiven two points $A = [1, 2]$ and $B = [4, 6]$.\n1. Compute the Euclidean distance between them.\n2. Compute the mean center of the two points.\n*(Write code to do it for any N-dimensional points)*"),
