cell("markdown","### 🔍 Reflection\nWhere is the elbow in your plot? Given how we generated the fake data (3 distinct blobs), does the elbow align with $K=3$?"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 3 — Olympiad Extension\n\n### Challenge: K-Means++ Initialization\nRandomly grouping points often results in slow convergence or getting trapped in local minima.\n**K-Means++** is a smarter initialization:\n1. Pick 1 random point as the first center.\n2. For each remaining point, compute its distance $D(x)$ to the nearest existing center.\n3. Pick the next center using Roulette Wheel Selection, where the probability of picking point $x$ is proportional to $D(x)^2$.\n4. Repeat until you have $K$ centers.\n\nImplement `kmeans_plus_plus(data, k)`."),
cell("code","# YOUR CODE HERE\npass"),
cell("markdown","### Chalkboard Defense\nExplain why K-Means++ initialization is vastly superior to purely random cluster assignment. What \"pathological\" starting state does it actively prevent?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Sketch</summary>\nRandom assignment might accidentally put two initial centers very close together inside the same data blob, while leaving another blob completely empty of centers. K-Means++ prevents this: because probabilities are proportional to distance squared, it actively seeks out data points that are *as far away as possible* from all existing centers, forcing the initial centers to spread out into the different natural clusters of the data.\n</details>\n\n---\n📚 **Next:** Algorithms 17 (Tic-Tac-Toe & Connect Four)")
